   <mods:abstract>Fluctuations in the French cabinet imperil the commercial negotiations
            between the United States and France. DuPont has been extremely helpful in the
            transactions, and every possible assistance should be extended to his son, who has gone
            to America. The influence of the Archbishop of Toulouse over the Queen is exercised
            through the Abbe who instructed the Queen in French before her marriage. The Archbishop
            succeeded to his position after the death of his enemy, Vergennes, and is disliked by
            many. It is said that once he bears the odium of certain economic reforms, the other
            ministers will remove him from the cabinet. The Archbishop is the individual who advised
            the withdrawal of France from entanglement in the Netherlands. Now that Holland is
            firmly in the grasp of France's enemies, France finds herself in a position where she
            cannot finance a war, and cannot borrow the necessary funds from Dutch bankers. Cautions
            Jay to look out for the European practice of bribing clerks in the Department of State
            for copies of diplomatic messages.</mods:abstract>
